// Exercise: cl-camp2
//
// Required:
// Create a file named 'r' that shows the letter "R" on a line when viewed
// using the 'cat' command.
//
// Problem summary:
// This exercise demonstrates understanding of how text files represent lines
// and how newline characters (\n) affect command-line output.
//
// Explanation:
// - The first line of this file contains only the character R followed by
//   a newline (the invisible \n character at the end of the line).
// - When you use 'cat r', it displays:
//     R
//   showing the single character and then moving to a new line.
// - When you use 'cat -e r', it reveals the newline by displaying:
//     R$
//
// What happens with echo:
// - Running 'echo "R" > r' writes the character R followed by a newline
//   into the file r.
// - The '>' symbol redirects the printed output into the file, replacing
//   any previous content.
// - Therefore, the resulting file contains exactly:
//     R\n
//   which matches the required output.
//
// Example output:
// $ cat -e r
// R$

R
